Baseball still has spreads that you see with other team sports, but they are often called a run-line instead of a point spread. As with the other point spreads, the run-line is a popular bet that requires a team to win or lose by a specified number of runs. Most run-line MLB odds will typically be set at anywhere from 0.5 to 3.5 runs. The favorite to win the game could have a MLB spread of -1.5 which means they must win by two or more runs to cover the spread. The underdog for the game would be set at +1.5 which means they can lose by one run or win the game outright for the bet to win. Each MLB run-line odds also has a price of making that bet, better known as juice or vig. For example, a -1.5 run line favorite could have vig of +115 (a payout of $150 for every $100 bet) while the +1.5 underdog could have vig of -135 (you need to bet $135 for every $100 you wish to win). If a game finishes with the favorites winning by the exact line margin shown on the point spread, bets are returned in an outcome known as a push.</p>\n<br />\n<h2><strong>Reading the World Series Championship Moneyline Odds</strong></h2>\n<p>Moneyline odds promise a % payoff when a gamblers chosen team wins the game straight-up. A favorites moneyline World Series Championship odds are denoted with a - as in (-200). Underdog moneylines are marked with a + as in a ML of (+350). Payoff is calculated differently for the betting odds in the favorites and underdogs markets, but always centered around the value of $100.An example of a moneyline could be the Detroit Tigers at -190 and the New York Yankees at +160. With odds of -190, the Detroit Tigers' moneyline bet would only return $52.60 on a $100 bet. The New York Yankees would return $160 on a $100 bet.</p>\n\n<p>View all <a href=\"https://sportsbook.fanduel.com/navigation/mlb\"><u>MLB odds</u></a> for upcoming games at FanDuel Sportsbook.</p>\n\n<br />\n<h2><strong>How To Read World Series Futures</strong></h2>\n\n<p>In the odds listed above, youll see a betting market (such as World Series Champion) and the current odds of each eligible team. The plus sign indicates an underdog and the minus sign indicates a favorite. For a favorite (e.g., -150), the number represents how much you need to bet to win $100, while for an underdog (e.g., +200), the number shows how much you'd win if you bet $100. For example, if a team's odds to win the division are +300, a $100 bet would yield a $300 profit if that team wins the division. If another team's odds are -200, you'd need to wager $200 to win $100. The lower the number (or higher if it's a negative), the more likely the team is expected to win.</li><br />\n<li><strong>Choosing your team:</strong> Pick the team you believe will win their division. If your chosen team finishes atop their division, your bet is a winner.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>MLB division odds can fluctuate throughout the season based on factors such as team performance, player injuries, trades, and other relevant news. Here's a simple breakdown of how MLB parlays work:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Choose your bet type:</strong> Decide whether you're betting on the moneyline (which team will win), the run line (the point spread), the over/under (total runs scored by both teams), or individual prop bets (RBIs, hits, etc.).</li><br />\n<li><strong>Select your bets:</strong> Choose the MLB games and individual players you want to include in your parlay. Remember, all selections must win for your parlay to be successful.</li><br />\n<li><strong>Determine your stake:</strong> A bet slip will populate with each selection. Now you can decide how much you want to wager.</li><br />\n<li><strong>Calculate potential winnings:</strong> The odds for your parlay will update with each bet you add or remove from your betslip. Your potential winnings are automatically calculated in the betslip when you enter a wager amount.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<p>It's important to remember that while the payouts for MLB parlays can be high, the risk is also increased because all selections must win. Factors such as team form, pitcher performance, head-to-head statistics, and weather conditions should be considered when selecting picks for an MLB parlay bet.</p>"},"652":{"id":652,"title":"MLB Series Winner Matchup Odds | FanDuel Sportsbook","footer":"<a href=\"https://sportsbook.fanduel.com/\">Sportsbook Odds</a> / <a href=\"https://sportsbook.fanduel.com/navigation/mlb\">MLB Odds</a> / <strong>Series Winner Odds</strong>\n<br />\n<br />\n\n<h1><strong>This Week's MLB Series Winner Odds and Betting</strong></h1>\n<p>Bet on who will win the upcoming regular season MLB series matchups with FanDuel Sportsbook.
